Your first pod.

The kubernetes equivalent of hello world is to use kubectl run to launch a pod named hello from the n-ginx alpine image. That single command does a surprising amount of work. Let us trace the sequence under the hood.

First, kubectl parses the command and builds a pod object in memory, a small document that says, I want a pod named hello whose only container is n-ginx alpine.

Second, it sends that object to the ay-pee-eye server as an h-t-t-p post.

Third, the ay-pee-eye server validates the object and writes it to et-see-dee.

Fourth, the scheduler notices there is a pod in et-see-dee with no node assigned. It picks a node, and with kind there is only one, then writes that decision back through the ay-pee-eye server.

Fifth, the kube-let on the chosen node sees that it has a new pod to run. It tells the container runtime to pull the n-ginx alpine image and start a container.

Sixth, the container starts. The kube-let updates the pod's status, from pending, to container creating, to running, and that status flows back into et-see-dee.

And finally, when you list the pods, you are simply reading the latest status from the ay-pee-eye server.

You did the work of the first two steps. Everything else happened on its own. Notice what kubectl run did not do. It did not connect to a server and launch a container directly. It wrote an object to a database and went home. The rest was a controller, somewhere, watching that database and reacting.

This is the heart of kubernetes. Declarative state, plus controllers that reconcile reality to match it. You will see this same pattern with every other object in this course.
